3/*++
4/* NAME
5/* cleanup_out_recipient 3
6/* SUMMARY
7/* envelope recipient output filter
8/* SYNOPSIS
9/* #include "cleanup.h"
10/*
11/* void cleanup_out_recipient(state, dsn_orig_recipient,
12/* dsn_notify, orig_recipient,
13/* recipient)
14/* CLEANUP_STATE *state;
15/* const char *dsn_orig_recipient;
16/* const char *dsn_notify;
17/* const char *orig_recipient;
18/* const char *recipient;
19/* DESCRIPTION
20/* This module implements an envelope recipient output filter.
21/*
22/* cleanup_out_recipient() performs virtual table expansion
23/* and recipient duplicate filtering, and appends the
24/* resulting recipients to the output stream. It also
25/* generates DSN SUCCESS notifications.
26/*
27/* Arguments:
28/* .IP state
29/* Cleanup server state.
30/* .IP dsn_orig_recipient
31/* DSN original recipient information.
32/* .IP dsn_notify
33/* DSN notify flags.
34/* .IP orig_recipient
35/* Envelope recipient as received by Postfix.
36/* .IP recipient
37/* Envelope recipient as rewritten by Postfix.
38/* CONFIGURATION
39/* .ad
40/* .fi
41/* .IP enable_original_recipient
42/* Enable orig_recipient support.
43/* .IP local_duplicate_filter_limit
44/* Upper bound to the size of the recipient duplicate filter.
45/* Zero means no limit; this may cause the mail system to
46/* become stuck.
47/* .IP virtual_alias_maps
48/* list of virtual address lookup tables.
49/* LICENSE
50/* .ad
51/* .fi
52/* The Secure Mailer license must be distributed with this software.
53/* AUTHOR(S)
54/* Wietse Venema
55/* IBM T.J. Watson Research
56/* P.O. Box 704
57/* Yorktown Heights, NY 10598, USA
58/*--*/
59

90/* cleanup_trace_append - update trace logfile */
91
92static void cleanup_trace_append(CLEANUP_STATE *state, RECIPIENT *rcpt,
93 DSN *dsn)
94{
95 MSG_STATS stats;
96
97 if (cleanup_trace_path == 0) {
98 cleanup_trace_path = vstring_alloc(10);
99 mail_queue_path(cleanup_trace_path, MAIL_QUEUE_TRACE,
100 state->queue_id);
101 }
102 if (trace_append(BOUNCE_FLAG_CLEAN, state->queue_id,
103 CLEANUP_MSG_STATS(&stats, state),
104 rcpt, "none", dsn) != 0) {
105 msg_warn("%s: trace logfile update error", state->queue_id);
106 state->errs |= CLEANUP_STAT_WRITE;
107 }
108}
109
110/* cleanup_verify_append - update verify daemon */
111
112static void cleanup_verify_append(CLEANUP_STATE *state, RECIPIENT *rcpt,
113 DSN *dsn, int verify_status)
114{
115 MSG_STATS stats;
116
117 if (verify_append(state->queue_id, CLEANUP_MSG_STATS(&stats, state),
118 rcpt, "none", dsn, verify_status) != 0) {
119 msg_warn("%s: verify service update error", state->queue_id);
120 state->errs |= CLEANUP_STAT_WRITE;
121 }
122}

124/* cleanup_out_recipient - envelope recipient output filter */
125
126void cleanup_out_recipient(CLEANUP_STATE *state,
127 const char *dsn_orcpt,
128 int dsn_notify,
129 const char *orcpt,
130 const char *recip)
131{
132 ARGV *argv;
133 char **cpp;
134
135 /*
136 * XXX Not elegant, but eliminates complexity in the record reading loop.
137 */
138 if (!var_enable_orcpt)
139 orcpt = "";
140 if (dsn_orcpt == 0)
141 dsn_orcpt = "";
142
143 /*
144 * Distinguish between different original recipient addresses that map
145 * onto the same mailbox. The recipient will use our original recipient
146 * message header to figure things out.
147 *
148 * Postfix 2.2 compatibility: when ignoring differences in Postfix original
149 * recipient information, also ignore differences in DSN attributes. We
150 * do, however, keep the DSN attributes of the recipient that survives
151 * duplicate elimination.
152 */
153#define STREQ(x, y) (strcmp((x), (y)) == 0)
154
155 if ((state->flags & CLEANUP_FLAG_MAP_OK) == 0
156 || cleanup_virt_alias_maps == 0) {
157 if ((var_enable_orcpt ?
158 been_here(state->dups, "%s\n%d\n%s\n%s",
159 dsn_orcpt, dsn_notify, orcpt, recip) :
160 been_here_fixed(state->dups, recip)) == 0) {
161 if (dsn_notify)
162 cleanup_out_format(state, REC_TYPE_ATTR, "%s=%d",
163 MAIL_ATTR_DSN_NOTIFY, dsn_notify);
164 if (*dsn_orcpt)
165 cleanup_out_format(state, REC_TYPE_ATTR, "%s=%s",
166 MAIL_ATTR_DSN_ORCPT, dsn_orcpt);
167 cleanup_out_string(state, REC_TYPE_ORCP, orcpt);
168 cleanup_out_string(state, REC_TYPE_RCPT, recip);
169 state->rcpt_count++;
170 }
171 }
172
173 /*
174 * XXX DSN. RFC 3461 gives us three options for multi-recipient aliases
175 * (we're treating single recipient aliases as a special case of
176 * multi-recipient aliases, one argument being that it is none of the
177 * sender's business).
178 *
179 * (a) Don't propagate ENVID, NOTIFY, RET, or ORCPT. If NOTIFY specified
180 * SUCCESS, send a "relayed" DSN.
181 *
182 * (b) Propagate ENVID, (NOTIFY minus SUCCESS), RET, and ORCPT. If NOTIFY
183 * specified SUCCESS, send an "expanded" DSN.
184 *
185 * (c) Propagate ENVID, NOTIFY, RET, and ORCPT to one recipient only. Send
186 * no DSN.
187 *
188 * In all three cases we are modifying at least one NOTIFY value. Either we
189 * have to record explicit dsn_notify records, or we must not allow the
190 * use of a per-message non-default NOTIFY value that applies to all
191 * recipient records.
192 *
193 * Alternatives (a) and (c) require that we store explicit per-recipient RET
194 * and ENVID records, at least for the recipients that are excluded from
195 * RET and ENVID propagation. This means storing explicit ENVID records
196 * to indicate that the information does not exist. All this makes
197 * alternative (b) more and more attractive. It is no surprise that we
198 * use (b) here and in the local delivery agent.
199 *
200 * In order to generate a SUCCESS notification from the cleanup server we
201 * have to write the trace logfile record now. We're NOT going to flush
202 * the trace file from the cleanup server; if we need to write bounce
203 * logfile records, and the bounce service fails, we must be able to
204 * cancel the entire cleanup request including any success or failure
205 * notifications. The queue manager will flush the trace (and bounce)
206 * logfile, possibly after it has generated its own success or failure
207 * notification records.
208 *
209 * Postfix 2.2 compatibility: when ignoring differences in Postfix original
210 * recipient information, also ignore differences in DSN attributes. We
211 * do, however, keep the DSN attributes of the recipient that survives
212 * duplicate elimination.
213 *
214 * In the case of a verify(8) request for a one-to-many alias, declare the
215 * alias address as "deliverable". Do not verify the individual addresses
216 * in the expansion because that results in multiple verify(8) updates
217 * for one verify(8) request.
218 *
219 * Multiple verify(8) updates for one verify(8) request would overwrite
220 * each other's status, and if the last status update is "undeliverable",
221 * then the whole alias is flagged as undeliverable.
222 */
223 else {
224 RECIPIENT rcpt;
225 DSN dsn;
226
227 argv = cleanup_map1n_internal(state, recip, cleanup_virt_alias_maps,
228 cleanup_ext_prop_mask & EXT_PROP_VIRTUAL);
229 if (argv->argc > 1 && (state->tflags & DEL_REQ_FLAG_MTA_VRFY)) {
230 (void) DSN_SIMPLE(&dsn, "2.0.0", "aliased to multiple recipients");
231 dsn.action = "deliverable";
232 RECIPIENT_ASSIGN(&rcpt, 0, dsn_orcpt, dsn_notify, orcpt, recip);
233 cleanup_verify_append(state, &rcpt, &dsn, DEL_RCPT_STAT_OK);
234 argv_free(argv);
235 return;
236 }
237 if ((dsn_notify & DSN_NOTIFY_SUCCESS)
238 && (argv->argc > 1 || strcmp(recip, argv->argv[0]) != 0)) {
239 (void) DSN_SIMPLE(&dsn, "2.0.0", "alias expanded");
240 dsn.action = "expanded";
241 RECIPIENT_ASSIGN(&rcpt, 0, dsn_orcpt, dsn_notify, orcpt, recip);
242 cleanup_trace_append(state, &rcpt, &dsn);
243 dsn_notify = (dsn_notify == DSN_NOTIFY_SUCCESS ? DSN_NOTIFY_NEVER :
244 dsn_notify & ~DSN_NOTIFY_SUCCESS);
245 }
246 for (cpp = argv->argv; *cpp; cpp++) {
247 if ((var_enable_orcpt ?
248 been_here(state->dups, "%s\n%d\n%s\n%s",
249 dsn_orcpt, dsn_notify, orcpt, *cpp) :
250 been_here_fixed(state->dups, *cpp)) == 0) {
251 if (dsn_notify)
252 cleanup_out_format(state, REC_TYPE_ATTR, "%s=%d",
253 MAIL_ATTR_DSN_NOTIFY, dsn_notify);
254 if (*dsn_orcpt)
255 cleanup_out_format(state, REC_TYPE_ATTR, "%s=%s",
256 MAIL_ATTR_DSN_ORCPT, dsn_orcpt);
257 cleanup_out_string(state, REC_TYPE_ORCP, orcpt);
258 cleanup_out_string(state, REC_TYPE_RCPT, *cpp);
259 state->rcpt_count++;
260 }
261 }
262 argv_free(argv);
263 }
264}
